<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUDGE LIKES DEFENDANTS TO WRITE THEIR WRONGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One way to right a wrong is to write a lot, a judge believes. 
</P>
<P>
 District Judge Mike Erwin sentenced a shoplifter to write 10,000 times: "I 
will not steal other people's property." 
</P>
<P>
 Another woman, who pleaded guilty to being an accessory after the fact to a 
burglary, had to write 10,000 times: "I will not do anything stupid again." 
</P>
<P>
 The judge, who has issued dozens of such sentences, said he hopes forcing 
defendants to write about their crimes will make them think about what they 
have done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
