<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: MOTORISTS' ATTACKS ON 
OFFICERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEAN MERL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The fatal shooting Dec. 27 of Manhattan Beach Police Officer Martin Ganz was 
only the latest in a series of incidents in recent years in which Southland 
police officers have been attacked during what appeared to be routine traffic 
stops: 
</P>
<P>
 * Aug. 6, 1993: Long Beach Police Officer Abel Dominguez was shot and 
critically wounded by friends of a motorist he had taken into custody in his 
patrol car. As Dominguez, who survived the attack, sat working at the car's 
computer console, two men approached the car, fired at him and fled with the 
motorist. Two suspects were later arrested. 
</P>
<P>
 * March 9, 1993: A motorcyclist on a quiet residential street in Garden Grove 
gunned down veteran Officer Howard E. Dallies Jr., who apparently had pulled 
over the cyclist. Neighbors who heard the shots and called 911 ran outside to 
find Dallies dying after being shot several times point-blank. The fatal bullet 
lodged in his abdomen, just below his bulletproof vest. 
</P>
<P>
 * Feb. 22, 1993: Compton Police Officers Kevin Michael Burrell and James Wayne 
MacDonald were killed by occupants of a red pickup they had stopped. Emerging 
from the truck firing, the occupants shot both officers several times; they 
died shortly afterward in a nearby hospital. 
</P>
<P>
 * Feb. 4, 1993: An unidentified Anaheim motorcycle officer escaped with minor 
injuries after a motorist he had stopped rammed his car into the officer's 
motorcycle, knocking him to the ground. The officer fired several shots at the 
car, and the driver and his passenger were arrested a short time later. A San 
Pedro man was arrested in April. 
</P>
<P>
 * Feb. 3, 1991: Two unidentified Los Angeles police officers were shot in 
North Hollywood as they tried to pull over the driver of a black sedan. Both 
officers recovered, but the driver, who turned out to be a wanted felon, died 
after the officers' return of his gunfire. 
</P>
<P>
 * Aug. 21, 1990: Los Angeles Traffic Officer Marvin Portillo was issuing a 
ticket for an expired registration of a car in the Wilshire district when the 
owner tried to run him over. The officer jumped onto the hood of the car to 
avoid being hit and was driven wildly around the neighborhood as the driver, 
who was later arrested, tried to shake him off. 
</P>
<P>
 * April 15, 1990: An unidentified Tustin police officer was shot at by a 
motorist who leaped out of his car after the officer pulled him over, then 
scuffled with the officer before pulling out a handgun and firing. The man 
missed, and police tracked him down and arrested him a few hours later. 
</P>
<P>
 * Aug. 13, 1989: Garden Grove Police Officer Darrow Halligan escaped injury 
when a motorist he had pulled over for running a stop sign shot twice at him. 
The motorist and a companion got out of the car and fled, with the motorist 
turning around and firing at Halligan as he chased them. 
</P>
<P>
 * June 3, 1989: An unidentified Buena Park police officer suffered a broken 
collarbone and cuts when a man he had stopped for making an illegal U-turn 
jumped into the officer's patrol car and drove off, dragging the officer as the 
two wrestled for control of the car. Police arrested the 19-year-old man. 
</P>
<P>
 * Oct. 26, 1988: Wilbur Carter, a Los Angeles motorcycle officer, escaped 
injury when a motorist with an Uzi machine gun opened fire on him in midday in 
Westwood Village. Carter had attempted to pull over the motorist for a traffic 
violation in the busy commercial area when the driver suddenly spun around and 
sped away, firing as he passed the officer.  
</P>
<P>
 * Jan. 9, 1988: California Highway Patrol Officer Gary Baker was shot in the 
face when he stopped a driver in Glassell Park. Baker survived after doctors 
removed a bullet that had lodged in his brain. 
</P>
<P>
 * Jan. 9, 1988: Los Angeles Police Officers Mike Laggart and Paul Nelson 
suffered minor injuries in Pacoima when a truck driver they pulled over for 
erratic driving attacked them with a four-inch hunting knife. The officers 
managed to knock the knife from the man's hand, subdue him and arrest him. 
</P>
<P>
 * Jan. 9, 1988: San Diego Police Officer Jerry Hartless was shot in the head 
by one of the occupants of a car he and his partner were trying to pull over. 
He died on Jan. 31. Six gang members were arrested. JEAN MERL 
</P>
</TEXT>
