<HEADLINE>
<P>
* RAYMOND WALKER, FORMER COUNTY TAX COLLECTOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Raymond Walker, Ventura County's treasurer and tax collector during the 1960s, 
died Saturday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
 Born on a farm in Saticoy, Walker was known as "Stringy" to his friends 
because of his tall, gaunt appearance as a young man.Except for a stint in the 
Navy during World War II and two years working in Hollywood, Walker spent his 
life in Ventura County. 
</P>
<P>
 He started working for the county as a motorcycle police officer in 1932, then 
went to work as a security officer at Warner Bros. studios, rubbing shoulders 
with the likes of Al Jolson and Dick Powell. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1938, he returned to Ventura and took a part-time job in the assessor's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
 Within two years, Walker worked his way up to the post of deputy treasurer, a 
position he held until he joined the Navy in 1942. 
</P>
<P>
 After returning from assignment in North Africa, he was appointed chief deputy 
treasurer and served in that post until being named treasurer in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
 Two years later he was elected to the combined post of treasurer and tax 
collector. He was reelected in 1966 and retired in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
 Survivors include his wife, Dortha, and daughters Betty Pfeiler and Binney 
Moss. 
</P>
<P>
 Services will be held at 10:30 a.m. Wednesday at Ted Mayr Funeral Home, 
Ventura. 
</P>
</TEXT>
