<HEADLINE>
<P>
REGIONAL PEOPLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Diane Sutter has been named president of Shamrock Holding's new television 
division. 
</P>
<P>
 The move was apparently designed to increase Shamrock's television station 
ownership.Shamrock Holdings Inc. is a Burbank investment firm owned by Roy E. 
Disney and his family. Roy E. Disney is a nephew of Walt Disney. 
</P>
<P>
 Sutter joined Shamrock in 1984, and most recently was executive vice president 
of operations for Shamrock Broadcasting, which manages Shamrock's radio station 
holdings. 
</P>
<P>
 Shamrock owns two Texas television stations, ABC affiliate KXXV in Waco, and 
CBS affiliate KTAB in Abilene. 
</P>
<P>
 Sutter said she plans to look for other television stations to buy. 
</P>
<P>
 * Roger A. Burlage has been named president and chief executive of Live 
Entertainment Inc., a Van Nuys videocassette distributor and retailer. 
</P>
<P>
 Burlage joins Live from Trimark Holdings Inc., an independent film and video 
production and distribution firm, where he was president and chief executive. 
He has also held positions at New World Pictures Ltd. and AVCO Corp. 
</P>
<P>
 * Roger Drue, chief executive officer of Encino-Tarzana Regional Medical 
Center and North Hollywood Medical Center, has resigned to become the chief 
executive at Kapiolani Health Care System in Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1989, Drue became chief executive of Tarzana Regional Medical Center and 
assumed the top post at the Encino hospital as well when it merged with Tarzana 
Regional in early 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 Also last year, Drue became chief executive at North Hollywood Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
 All three hospitals are owned fully or in part by American Medical Holdings. 
</P>
<P>
 David Levinsohn, formerly head of Sherman Oaks Hospital, has been named 
interim CEO of the three hospitals. 
</P>
