<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPECIAL REPORT: MOVING TO THE VALLEY; NEWCOMERS ARRIVE ON WAVE OF HOPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 They've come, despite the closing aerospace plants, crime and languishing 
public schools. They've come, despite graffiti, gloomy news reports and streets 
lined with For Sale signs. 
</P>
<P>
 Bucking the trend in recession-dogged Los Angeles, people are still moving to 
the San Fernando Valley.  
</P>
<P>
 And while old-timers complain of the Valley's demise, these newcomers still 
see the promise of a better life here. They've defied the common wisdom and 
come here to buy homes, open businesses, flee from crime and start anew amid 
the Valley's fast-changing ethnic mix. 
</P>
<P>
 And while those leaving the Southland still garner much of the publicity, 
those who are just arriving have something to say as well. 
</P>
<P>
 These pages represent a view of the Valley through the eyes of people who 
arrived during the past year -- what they like and what they don't like about 
their new home, and what they hope to make of its future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
